Hey all, I read that TWAPs were initially introduced in Uniswap V2 but I couldn‚Äôt understand the reasoning behind it. What problem do TWAPs solve? What are sandwich attacks? I read the below excerpt from a medium article but couldn‚Äôt understand the logic behind it. How would a whale profit from submitting a large order and causing substantial slippage? Would you be able to give me an answer from an example pool of ETH/USDT trading at 100.

> Smart contracts using AMM spot prices as oracles can be easily exploited through sandwich attacks ‚Ä?an attack vector where a malicious entity makes a large trade within an AMM liquidity pool to shift the price in their favor, then uses that distorted pricing to unfairly siphon value from smart contracts using that AMM liquidity pool as a spot price oracle. Normally, such an attack would only be possible by well-capitalized entities like whales, but flash loans allow anyone in the world to become a temporary whale and perform such a sandwich attack.
You buy half the pool, raising the price, right before the other guy buys, forcing him to buy the more expensive token, and then sell it, dumping the price.

But then you need to have the information that the other guys will definitely buy from this pool right? So you basically frontrun them. Otherwise any rational trader who sees the price would just trade from a CEX no?
Yes sandwhichers frontrun trades by observing the mempool and bribing a miner to put their transactions before and after the trade waiting in the mempool

Let‚Äôs say I submit an order to buy ETH at $2k from the ETH/USDT pool on Uniswap. To pay lower gas fees, I want the transaction to get executed in 1min. Let‚Äôs assume that the pool has low TVL and that you, a sandwich attacker, have enormous capital. You learn that I have submitted the transaction and before it‚Äôs executed, you submit a massive order buying half the pool and spiking up ETH price to $20k in the pool. You pay a high gas fee to the miner so that the transaction is executed ASAP. Now, my ETH order is executed at $20k. Then you sell all the ETH you bought. How do you make a profit from this? What is your weighted average cost and your weighted average selling price?

Can‚Äôt I avoid this by setting up a max slippage or paying high gas fees so the transaction is executed faster?
What if I don‚Äôt have enough USDT to buy ETH at $20k? Wouldn‚Äôt your strategy fail?
How do you know that I submitted an order? Do you see it in the mempool in Etherscan?
Yes max slippage. No higher gas. They'll outbid you if the trade is profitable.

You can look up any token on dexttools and it'll show you sandwich attacks in red.

If no slippage, you'll just buy far less eth since you'll buy it at $20k. Rather than getting 1 eth you'll get .1

mempool sniping is too risky and not done anymore (appart from arbitrage bots vs other arb bots)
Bots now use <https://github.com/flashbots/pm>
well they need to monitor the mempool for opps before they can submit to flashbots. i think you're thinking private gas auctions, which yes people don't do any more. but they still mempool snipe
yes üôÇ everything else is true
(it's a detail)

Sometimes the gas included is too low and the transaction will not be processed. You probably need to speed up or cancel the transaction in you wallet.

Fix stuck transactions in MetaMask: <https://metamask.zendesk.com/hc/en-us/articles/360015489251-How-to-Speed-Up-or-Cancel-a-Pending-Transaction>

Fix stuck transactions in trust wallet: <https://www.publish0x.com/the-crypt/quick-guide-to-fixing-stuck-ethereum-transactions-xgdvgkv>

Fix stuck transactions in coinbase wallet: <https://cryptorachel.medium.com/how-to-replace-pending-transaction-in-coinbase-custodial-wallet-9821ff699041>

@terumask 
The app isn't the uniswap protocol, it is fully runned by uniswap labs (the app) and the governance has nothing to say about it.
The governance owns `uniswap.eth` and could propose it's own app if it wish too but it hasn't currently done anything.
Many people have forked the app, and just removed all the restrictions, all of thoses restrictions are just done in your browser, the actual uniswap protocol on chain isn't censorable (like not at all, even the governance couldn't vote to censor anything in the protocol).

Other apps such as zapper, 1inch or paraswap which may access uniswap under the hood works perfectly fine and have no restrictions (except if they implemented some themself which I don't belive they do).

@Libertarian Salvation 
Uniswap is made by uniswap labs (a small US based company).
They have been paid a lots of money from the ethereum fundation at first.
And now owns a lot of UNI, so their incentives are to make uniswap better and hope that this makes UNI more expensive, so they could sell some UNI at a better price in the future.

The main incentives behind banning some tokens are tiny legal things, (such as not going to prison, or not receiving a lawsuit from the SEC or FCC because they are selling unofficial securities, ...). And remember that this is only for `app.uniswap.org` you are completely free to download uniswap's interface source code, remove the ban list, and build it, it takes ~10 minutes and you will have 0 bans or just use an other version from someone which already made this.

Not sure if the "near zero" you said indicates the price or quantity of the token. If the token you provide LP is A/B: 
1. If the price of token A drops down to near zero, then the LP provider will automatically absorb more A (that is, the B token will be exchanged by other users), causing the entire LP token value turn to 0
2. If the liquidity is insufficient and the demand for token A is large, users will exchange B for A, causing the price of A to rise.

What has happen is that coinbase did a swap doing `RSR -> USDC`, but the `USDC / RSR` pool is really really tiny so it loose all of his money to price impact and arb bots.
Uniswap's UI would never have made that trade, uniswap's UI would have made `RSR -> ETH -> USDC` likely, and have a price impact of ~1% (not ~99.9%).
The smart contract doesn't check for this kind of routing stuff because it's just too expensive and would cost too much gas. This task is delegated to the UI, but coinbase's UI doesn't do that.

Uniswap does not Set, regulate or control prices. These are set by the person who makes the pool, and then are governed only by the trades made. __Uniswap receives no money from this at all.__ 
Uniswap is a set of decentralized contracts written and created on ethereum. No one but the Uniswap governance has any control over the contracts. Anyone anywhere can use the Uniswap contracts, and these contracts will exist as long as Ethereum does. This contract has no ability to remove tokens, change prices or anything. Once a token is written in to the contract, it can not be removed. This is what makes Uniswap Decentralized
Your purchase was an investment into a token ecosystem that is managed Only by the token authors. As with all investments there is a risk of loss. Sometimes the price goes up, sometimes it goes down, this is based purely on people buying or selling.
I'm sorry your investment was a loss, but Uniswap has nothing to do with your choices, or the funds in the uniswap contracts. Uniswap has no way to control or change any of this period.

@here I made a transaction from my Metamask Wallet via Uniswapp selling 4MM tokens on the 6th of July and the funds still haven‚Äôt been credited to my wallet. The swap was for ETH transaction 0x0f052498ae9f6c3053fed92f25fcebb3f8cc9c41228c3b5f433543f988b013d4.

Hi JaniT, this is an approve transaction only. The first time you do a swap from a particular token, you need to do 2 transactions. 

Step 1 is the Approve. This makes it so you can swap that token on Uniswap. From then on, you can swap from that token with only one step. 

Step 2 is the Swap. This is where your tokens are actually swapped for something else. 

Note: You are charged an Ethereum transaction fee each for both the Approve and Swap, just like any other transaction in Ethereum.

You can go back to https://app.uniswap.org/ to proceed with step 2. You should no longer see the Approve button now, just Swap.

I'll rephrase my example.
- If you have lots of your token in the pool, the pool will be more resistant to raise in price and propose a low price impact to swappers who are buying your token.
- If you have lots of ETH in the pool, the pool will be more resistant to drops in price and propose a low price impact to swappers who are selling your token.

So for example in V3 you can have lots of ETH resisting a price drop but few tokens so a price raise would be easy.

Sorry if this is the wrong channel for this, but not sure if those of you living in the US are tracking the infrastructure bill going through Congress but there is some pretty negative statements in it related to Crypto policy. Something other industry's do well is arming people with information to help them craft a message to their representatives/senators. I was hoping the Crypto Council would have this but I couldn't find anything similar. Below is the message I sent to all of my representatives/Senators, feel free to send this on and hopefully it helps:

Ma'am,

I would ask you to confer with your fellow Senators and remove the crypto portions of the infrastructure bill. First, crypto policy has no place in an infrastructure bill. It deserves its own bill that can stand on its own and not be grouped together. Second, the portions inside the bill are completely unrealistic to enact and would erode momentum that the United States currently has in becoming a leader in the crypto world and continuing our leadership in the financial sector instead of ceding ground to China and other nations that do not respect human rights or the rest of our freedom-loving values. If the Senate does not remove this portion from the bill, you vote against the infrastructure bill. Last, I would ask you to talk to Senator Warren about crypto. I take offense to being called a "shadowy super coder." I have served honorably in the US military for more than a decade, and many in the crypto world want to build crypto to be a more transparent financial system than the current financial system we have. We also believe it will open access to funding and banking to many who don't have that access today. I highly recommend you and Senator Warren listen to the Bankless podcasts, weekly rollup, released each Friday to learn more about crypto.

This summer I've been working on analyzing and visualizing DEXs. When using UniSwap it may be easy to forget about the complex connectedness of token pairs behind the scenes. To visualize what's going on, I queried the data from the GraphQL API and used Gephi to create the network visualization of UniSwap. The edges are token pairs (liquidity pools) and the nodes are tokens. I also made the node sizes proportional to how many pools they're in (the big one in the bottom left is Ether). If you want to check out some more of my data visualizations and findings check out my Twitter https://twitter.com/eljhfx. If y'all are interested I can also start sharing some of the Uniswap related work here.

@Bing¬≤  @Â§©‰Ωø ¬∑ Shib  @undoubted08 Hey may I know if this image above is a one time payment for the slp transaction? I hate when members here are giving assistance saying they are admins here
it is a one time payment
It's you talking to SLP, saying: "Hey, do you see that thing : 'Uniswap V3 Router' (or V2), well I trust it, so if it asks to take my SLPs, it can, I allow it".
Thanks
@Zyy then uniswap is able to use `transferFrom(yourWallet,TheDestinationPool,Amount)` and spend your SLP, this will pull SLP from your wallet and move them in the destination pool

@Zyy Uniswap is not dumb, and so in practice it's not your wallet that is used, but `msg.sender` which is the caller of the router, so if I call the router, it's my wallet, if you call the router it's your wallet, so you have access to your wallet on uniswap, and I have access on mine, ...

Hahaha oke, is was looking at that and the V2 router code. Trying to understand why the router first transfer tokens to the pair contract
this is to save gas, just read the V2 `swap` code, it should make sense in ~10 minutes

@tom The goal is that this allows to do stuff like this in multihops paths :
```
Router transferFrom seller to Pair 1
Pair 1 transfer to Pair 2
Pair 2 transfer to Recipient
```
While a more classical transferFrom approach would need :
```
Router transferFrom seller to himself
Router approve pair 1
Pair 1 transferFrom router to herself
Pair 1 transfer to router
Router approve pair 2
Pair 2 transferFrom router to herself
Pair 2 transfer to recipient
```
Ah, I understand! Thank you.
And the pair compare it's true balance against the last known one, gives any extra to the seller
Actually my example is a bit missleading because the pool need to call balanceOf for herself on the token, but that a staticall so much cheaper

Hahahaha, Polynetwork breach was a feature right üòÜ . Yeah printing is what I am doing right now, I only find it pretty difficult to find out what went wrong in production/on-chain. Actually when I am typing this, it isn't even that different from non-blockchain development, its the same thing.

> Polynetwork breach was a feature right
No that was just bad architecture design.
Also some people make it sounds like it's new, no it's not, we have seen this attack already, it's just that it was done on multisigs / upgrade proxy, not on a runner contract like that, but not many peoples have created thoses kinds of contracts already so it's expected.

My advice to that is just:
- Test your code, a lot
- Make other people review your code.
- And write "secure by design" thing, so for example something that have powers must be very restrained. So for example, don't give admin powers to a contract that is meant to execute random transactions from strangers on the internet.
Ah okay. I can only imagine the difficulty in the development of these complex systems. Thanks for the advice.
That true, it's hard, so just don't make it complex
Keep things simple
I mean, have simple rules to follow

V2 or V3 ?
It is V3  https://app.uniswap.org/#/add/0xC02aaA39b223FE8D0A0e5C4F27eAD9083C756Cc2/0x3F382DbD960E3a9bbCeaE22651E88158d2791550/10000

I see if I understand. Let say that I choose a range. When I have choosed a range. Now I am forced to invest for example 200$ in USDC and 500$ WETH if the Interface shows this? I mean that the $ amounts ratios are fixed by the interface for different Ranges?

The ratio is calculated by the range.
So if you choose a range you need to follow the ratio of that range.
But you can change the range to change the ratio.
If you want to spend 0 USDC and only your token, you can create a range like this:
```
- Current price 100$
- Range start 101$ (or anything above the current price)
- Range end 5000$ (or anything above the start of the range)
```
In practice people will be able to buy your token, but not sell it.
Note that if some peoples buy your token, this will exchange some of your token to USDC in the pool (that what swapping is in reality), so your token will be sellable using the newly USDC found in the pool.

This is an `Approve` transaction only, not the actual swap yet. The first time you do a swap from a particular token, you need to do 2 transactions. 

**Step 1** is the `Approve`. This makes it so you can swap that token on Uniswap. From then on, you can swap from that token with only one step. NOTE: Each token requires a different Approval for each Uniswap version (V1, V2, or V3). 

**Step 2** is the `Swap`. This is where your tokens are actually swapped for something else. 

**Note:** You are **charged** an Ethereum transaction fee a.k.a. gas fees each for **both** the `Approve` and `Swap`, just like any other transaction in Ethereum.

You can go back to https://app.uniswap.org/ and enter the value you want to swap to proceed with step 2. You should no longer see the `Approve` button now, just `Swap`.

Hey! If I provide liquidity for a pool, let's say DAI/ETH, I'll get LP back. Then after say a month of trading (let's ignore any other liq. providers adding/removing liquidity) the fees that have been paid in make the LP worth more than it was a month ago. The Uniswap platform shows this profit on the accounts page, under positions. If I add more liquidity to the same pool will I get a new position for the same pair, or will the platform merge it into the same position? The reason I ask is, it wouldn't be simple at that point to calculate total fees earned, as the LP was acquired at different times - essentially the LP had a different "price" so how could you calculate the profit?

TL;DR; if you add liquidity to the same pair twice do you get multiple positions in the accounts screen (which show your profit) or do you get one position and Uniswap does some magic to calculate profit?
every time you add *new* liquidity you will mint a new NFT and create a brand new position. you can however add liquidity to an existing position, and this will not mint a new NFT
the "profit" is simply the amount of tokens you received in fees times their current market value
the amount of liquidity you have in the position is irrelevant

From the V3 Whitepaper: ```As a result, in v3, the pool contract does not implement the
ERC-20 standard. Anyone can create an ERC-20 token contract in

reinvestment of, collected fees.```

I literally NEED this. Do you know if somebody already implemented an ERC20 representation of a position for V3? Thanks!

We are working on a protocol  where we want these positions to serve as collateral for other investments and having an ERC20 which represent liquidity in V3 would be awesome. Any guidance would be appreciated!

@Julian Rodriguez
> We are working on a protocol  where we want these positions to serve as collateral for other investments and having an ERC20 which represent liquidity in V3 would be awesome. Any guidance would be appreciated!
You don't need an ERC20, I understand it makes your work a few multiplications and divisions.
But if you don't let users borrow positions of others you can just limit each user to X position maximum (or require an additional deposit that will be lost uppon liquidation per new position) to avoid users creating a gas deadlock and just use the V3 NFT positions and for each position fetch what is the current value at time of liquidation.

Thanks for the response! I dont think I fully understand the last part. But Im thinking another approach would be to "wrap" somehow the NFT positions to make them behave more like an ERC20? The reason I need it as ERC20 is because it coexists with other assets in a pool, all ERC20 so I really want them to have that behavior (but underneath could be V3 Uniswapt NFT positions). Do you see this feasible?

You can't wrap things that doesn't have the same value (or rather you can't wrap things that have values that doesn't scale the same way).
Imagine creating a wrapped token that contains WBTC and WETH.

@Julian Rodriguez I really think if you want V3, either you use an automated liquidity managment (which aren't that good and doesn't allows cool stuff such as sell order margin trading) and an ERC20. Or accept that V3 is hard and write some snow flake code for uniswap V3.

What I mean, is let's assume you allow USDT, WETH and WBTC in your platform.
When someone wants to deposit an NFT, first you check it's an official uniswap one, and what are the tokens, if both tokens are in your token list then you accept the NFT and then you treat the NFT as it's own custom token.
So when someone try to liquidate, you fetch how much underlying the NFT is worth, calculate health factor with thoses new tokens if that bellow your threashold, allow liquidation.

The issue with this is that someone could create 2000 NFTs borrow a lot, and then imagine the price of the NFTs falls down compared to the collateral this would be unliquidatable due to a gas cost too high. So then you can do like what Liquity does, ask users to stake 300$ per new NFT, so when someone liquidate that NFT he would get the extra 300$ to repay the gas costs.
(actually X$ gas costs can't work because liquidations are each O(N) on number of NFTs, and there must be N liquidation per NFT at worst so it's `O(N*2)` where N = number of NFT)
so you must just accept to limit at X NFTs per vault
Wow very interesting...
Yeah I see the implications

@Julian Rodriguez The only scalling issue with my solution is that will require liquidators to track the evolution of many NFTs (because there can up to `3 * number of vault` NFTs), but since this is running offchain I don't think that is actually an issue.

@Julian Rodriguez Ah and also, you need to be carefull with the pools, check that someone isn't manipulating the price of the NFTs (someone could sandwitch your protocol, making the price really high so lots of NFTs would become liquidatable, but that is classical oracle safety stuff)

Hi serega, this is an approve transaction only. The first time you do a swap from a particular token, you need to do 2 transactions. 

Step 1 is the Approve. This makes it so you can swap that token on Uniswap. From then on, you can swap from that token with only one step. 

Step 2 is the Swap. This is where your tokens are actually swapped for something else. 

Note: You are charged an Ethereum transaction fee each for both the Approve and Swap, just like any other transaction in Ethereum.

You can go back to https://app.uniswap.org/ to proceed with step 2. You should no longer see the Approve button now, just Swap.

Sounds, good, I hope my questions don't sound stupid, I try to make everything as clear as possible. 
q1: If I provide liquidity in the range of $20 -> $30, and the price goes from $25 to $35, do I only collect fees as the price rises from $25 to $35? 
q2: As soon as the price passes $30, is all of my liquidity one token? 
q3: if the price drops to $15, did I essentially place a limit order of $20, if all my liquidity is now a single token?

1. You only earn fees when the price is within your range. 
2. So if it passes $30 you'll stop earning fees and your assets will be converted into one side of the pair. 
3. Correct. If price passes any of the extremes of your range then all assets will be converted into the asset that has the lower value (the one being "dumped")

If i'm understanding about impermanant loss correctly, as long as i wait for arbitragers to rebalance the liquidity pool to match the price of both coins in my liquidity pair, I won't experience any loss. Correct?

No, it's the price ratio between the 2 assets that you need to check. If you deposit and withdraw when the price ratio is different (doesn't matter which direction it goes) then you'll take a loss. If fees don't fully make up for the losses then you'll take a net loss. If fees fully offset the losses, then you'll take a net gain.

Hi there, The first time you do a swap from a particular token, you need to do 2 transactions. 

Step 1 is the Approve. This makes it so you can swap that token on Uniswap. From then on, you can swap from that token with only one step. 

Step 2 is the Swap. This is where your tokens are actually swapped for something else. 

Note: You are charged an Ethereum transaction fee each for both the Approve and Swap, just like any other transaction in Ethereum.

You can go back to https://app.uniswap.org/ to proceed with step 2. You should no longer see the Approve button now, just Swap.

Thanks for your time!
My personal recommendation is to just not use one.  I haven't seen any evidence that they help in a meaningful way.
I suspect it falls into the trap of people feeling like "doing something" is better than "doing nothing" even when doing something causes more harm than help.
I have seen many servers where there are a large number of users who get stuck or give up on some custom verification step, or servers where the verification bot breaks, or it has a confusing UX.
Meanwhile, on all of those servers I still see massive DM spam/scams, suggesting that the verification isn't actually helping.
If instead, just the built-in Discord moderation and welcome tools were used you wouldn't have stuck/frustrated users and you would have the same amount of spam/scams to deal with.

This is anecdotal of course, and others may have a different experience, but I haven't seen anyone who actually did a proper A/B test of any kind (I'm not even sure how you would do that without too many confounding variables).

I have a question about "Auto" slippage setting. In situations like in a token launch where you want to send a transaction through fast will "Auto" slippage be the correct setting? Does this feature have a cap or will it use as much slippage as possible to get the transaction through faster? Would you recommend something else if the speed of the transaction is the main factor?
We are the NFT project on Ethereum. Our project is used to record the history of Ethereum and excellent projects. We love uniswap, so we made NFT elements for it. Can I send it?
Increasing slippage tolerance is only to account for fees if it's a fee-on-transfer token or if it's a volatile token and if you think the price will move, how much are you willing to tolerate.
No, ads allowed. Sorry.
Please read #üìô‚îÇrules

@Psychadelic Banana It's generally not recommended to increase the slippage tolerance since you will risk the trade from getting frontrun. If say, you set it to 50%, that means you are okay with only receiving 50% of your swap. Frontrunning bots will see this and will profit from your swap.

If you want the transaction to be confirmed faster, increase the gas fee.
Unlike V2 where fees are added to the pool, V3 is separate. There is a `Collect Fee` button in the V3 interface when you view your liquidity pools.
Let's say hypothetically you set to 100% it will only move as much as necessary?
50% is the highest slippage tolerance you can set.

If you set it to even 10%, there are bots that will see your transaction even before your swap is confirmed and you will most likely get a bad deal out of it. So best to keep it low and only account for what is necessary.
Yes this is true
I think it's 2 different transactions(remove liquidity and collect fee) so you'll have to pay gas twice. But I am not sure.

quick question I swap SLP to ETH using Uniswap, but once I confirm the transaction the SLP wasn't  swap to ETH but the gas fee was deducted, anyone could help me? please!

Hi there, this is an approve transaction only, not the actual swap yet. Approve` transactions doesn't swap anything. This just lets the token contract know that you are allowing Uniswap to use your tokens for swapping. Approves are part of the ERC-20 standard, so it's required. And every transaction you make on Ethereum costs gas fee. You can monitor current gas price here: https://www.gasnow.org/ you can continue to do the swap now, or do it later if you want (wait for the gas price to go down).

Contracts are dumb machine, it's obvious to you and me but you still need to tell the token that you are trusting uniswap because nothing is obvious for a machine, they just do what they have been told to do.

> I just want to understand what I am paying fee for
In the code, you call `token.approve(uniswapRouter, MAX)` this then allow uniswap to call `token.transferFrom(yourAcount, RecipientPool, tradeValue)`, this will transfer some `token` from your account to the pool (while if uniswap were to call `token.transfer` which doesn't require approval first, it would attempt to transfer from uniswap router's account to the pool which doesn't make sense).

Uniswap approve `115792089237316195423570985008687907853269984665640564039457584007913129639935` tokens because that the maximum value that fits into 256 bits so you never have to approve again because you are just never gonna trade more than `115792089237316195423570985008687907853269984665640564039457584007913129639935` tokens.

Thx and can u explain to me (im new to crypto) why gas fee are so high on opensea but like on uniswap to swap its not so high?

gas fees are the price relative to the work the miners do. The gwei price  multiplied by the amount of data is the transaction cost. So the Gass limit is the amount of work that is being done in the tx (which changes based on the contract). The gas Gwei is the cost for that transactions speed and determines if the miners will accept it. This is based off of network traffic and race conditions to get the tx mined fastest.  better descriptions can be found at ethereum.org
